        <tr><td>
<a class="key" href="../../rcd"><div  data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Shortcut to Radio Monitoring Service (Netherlands)" class="key">RCD</div></a><a class="key" href="../../../manuf/essa"><div  data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Shortcut to Essa Electronics (SPI)" class="key">Essa</div></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="key" href="../../dare/cr3000c"><div  data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Forward to CR-3000/C" class="key right">CR-3000/C &rarr;</div></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;        <div style="height: 20px;"></div>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          <b>BMR-1000</b>
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
<b>Frequency detector</b>
<font color=#F52E00>- under construction</font>
<br />
<br />
<b>BMR-1000</b> is a mobile frequency counter with built-in field-strength
indicator and acoustic feedback, jointly developed in 1995
by the <a href="../../rcd"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: Dutch Radio Monitoring Service ...">Dutch Radio Monitoring Service (RCD) <sup><font color="#FF8800">2</font></sup> </span></a> and
external contractor <a href="../../../manuf/essa"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: Essa Electronics">Essa Electronics</span></a> in
IJmuiden (Netherlands). Manufactured by <span class="short" aria-label="Essa Electronics (SPI)" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../../manuf/essa" class="short" >Essa</a></span> <sup><font color="#FF8800">1</font></sup>
the device was used to determine the frequency of a mobile
radio system in close proximity, in order to be able to intercept it.
The <span class="short" aria-label="Radio Monitoring Service (Netherlands)" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../rcd/index.htm" class="short" >RCD</a></span>
mainly used it to find clandestine users of the frequency spectrum.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The device has the form factor of a regular car stereo, allowing it to be
installed unobtrusively in any existing mobile intercept station.
It is powered by the 12V battery of the vehicle.
All connections are located at the rear panel, whilst the controls and readout
are at the front panel.
<br />
<br />
The BMR-1000 has a frequency range from 30 MHz to 1 GHz and will automatically
lock onto the strongest signal in its vicinity, which is usu&shy;ally the clandestine
station under investigation.
When locked, the 6-digit display will instantly show the
frequency of the intercepted signal.
          </font></td>
          <td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
          <td align=center valign=top width=100>
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" ><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/303071/009/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="BMR-1000 frequency counter">
<a href="img/303071/009/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="BMR-1000 frequency counter">
            <img src="img/303071/009/small.jpg"
             style="
             max-width: 618px;
            "
             align="left"
             vspace="4"
             alt="BMR-1000 frequency counter"
             border=0
             width=298 height=200
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The name of the device (<b>BMR-1000</b>) is derived from the initials of three people: <u>B</u>en and <u>M</u>art &ndash; both working at the <span class="short" aria-label="Radio Monitoring Service (Netherlands)" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../rcd/index.htm" class="short" >RCD</a></span>
&ndash; and <u>R</u>ob - the developer at <span class="short" aria-label="Essa Electronics (SPI)" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../../manuf/essa" class="short" >Essa</a></span> (<span class="short" aria-label="Small Practical Innovation" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../../manuf/essa" class="short" >SPI</a></span>) <a href="#ref_3">[3]</a><a href="#ref_4">[4]</a>.
<b>1000</b> stands for the maxi&shy;mum frequency of 1 GHz.
The BMR-1000 was first manufactured in 1995. The design was impro&shy;ved in 1997.
It has an f/100 output that can be
connected to the <a href="../../pan2000"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: PAN-2000">PAN-2000</span></a> intercept receiver for instant synchronisation. The BMR-1000 was succeeded in 1999 by the <a href="../../dare/cr3000c"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: Dare CR-3000/C">Dare CR-3000/C</span></a>.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width="50" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr>
        <td style="border-top: 1px solid #aaa;"><img src="../img/blank.gif" width="1" height="5"/></td>
        </tr></table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr><td>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#888888><small>
          <ol>
          <li>
Since 1995, <span class="short" aria-label="Essa Electronics (SPI)" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../../manuf/essa" class="short" >ESSA</a></span> is known as
  <span class="short" aria-label="Small Practical Innovation" data-balloon-pos="up"><a href="../../../manuf/essa" class="short" >SPI</a></span> and is located in Heerhugowaard (Netherlands).
          </li>
          <li>
Between 1989 and 2001, the
  <a href="../../rcd/index.htm"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="More about: Dutch Radio Monitoring Service">Dutch Radio Monitoring Service</span></a> (now: RDI)
  was known as HDTP-RDR. <font color="#E7E">&#10148;</font>&nbsp;<a href="../../rcd/index.htm#names">More</a>
          </ol>
          </small></font></td></tr>
        </table>
